# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __itruediv__, __ifloordiv__, __imod__ across all 10 asyncio subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 10 classes x 3 methods = 30 rows.
# __itruediv__: false for all 10 — in-place true division is not defined.
# __ifloordiv__: false for all 10 — in-place floor division is not defined.
# __imod__: false for all 10 — in-place modulo is not defined.
# All 30 values are false.
# asyncio types are designed for coroutine-based concurrency — their entire
#   API surface is expressed through await, async with, async for, and
#   explicit method calls. Neither forward division/modulo operators (wave 659)
#   nor their in-place augmented assignment variants appear in any asyncio
#   type's __dict__.
# asyncio.Event note: Event manages a simple boolean flag (set/clear/wait);
#   it defines no arithmetic protocol of any kind.
# asyncio.Lock/Condition note: mutual-exclusion synchronization objects;
#   augmented assignment operators have no meaning for lock state.
# asyncio.Semaphore/BoundedSemaphore note: the permit counter is encapsulated
#   and not exposed for any arithmetic, including /=, //=, %=.
# asyncio.Queue note: Queue is an ordered item store. Items are managed
#   solely through put()/get() coroutine calls; no augmented arithmetic is
#   defined from any side.
# str.__mod__ distinction: Python's built-in str defines __mod__ to implement
#   the % string formatting operator. asyncio queue types are not str subclasses
#   and do not inherit or implement any such protocol.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

